Interpol has confirmed it knew about the stolen passports but said no authorities checked its vast databases on stolen documents before the jet departed.

Warning that 'only a handful of countries' routinely make such checks, Interpol secretary general Ronald Noble chided authorities for 'waiting for a tragedy to put prudent security measures in place at borders and boarding gates'.

There was no indication that the two men had anything to do with the tragedy, but the thefts of the passports added a twist to the plane's mysterious disappearance.

